<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-290-814  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 290 814.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telecommunications  May 1989 v23 n5 p55(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Capital budgeting for fiber. (Public Network Services) (telephonecompanies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Egan, Bruce L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many foresee a fiber-to-the-home battle between telephonecompanies (telcos) and cable TV operators, saying if the telcoslose out in the legal and regulatory struggle over provision ofentertainment video, they will not be motivated to deploy fiberoptics to the home.andP;  This interpretation is erroneous.andP;  In fact,the telephone companies see fiber in the network as a way to staycompetitive regardless of regulatory or legal restrictions againstprovision of video services and being first with fiber isimportant to them.andP;  There appears to be money enough for fiber.andO;Capital spending is high among the telcos, and the money is mostlyinternally generated, without any borrowing.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber opticsTelephone companiesCable TVTelecommunicationsCapital InvestmentTelephone systemsCompetitionGovernment RegulationNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>